node.text: Sam, Golden Retriever (16 y/o), Upper West Side, New York, NY • We’ve partnered with @thefarmersdog to tell the story of Sam, a senior rescue dog who’s living a long, fulfilling and healthy life. The Farmer’s Dog is helping senior dogs in shelters find homes in time for the holidays – follow the link at the end of the video to see adoptable seniors in shelters all across the country so hopefully you can find a Sam, too.

node.text: GIVEAWAY: Elsa, Simon, Artie & Brody (Husky mix, Jindo mix, Hound mix & Goldendoodle) • “This isn't their first sleepover, but it is their first sleepover in matching pajamas.” • We teamed up with @thecompanystore to throw the Dogist Dogs a slumber party! If you want to win your own slumber party essentials (matching human & dog pajamas, complete sheet set, duvet cover, dog bed, AND a full DOGS set from @thedogistshop) make sure you follow both @thedogist & @thecompanystore and tag a friend below – each comment is an entry to win! Winner will be announced Friday 8/6. Link in bio to shop.

node.text: Panko, Australian Labradoodle (9 m/o), 28th & 7th Ave., New York, NY • “He was a surprise for my kids during the pandemic. My youngest son was begging for a dog hourly for three years. He’s a dream dog. He’s brought so much joy to our apartment. We named him Panko because I accidentally ordered 20 lbs of panko crumbs from Baldor around when we got him. His middle name is Messi – my son is a big soccer fan.”

node.text: Milly, Dachshund (2 y/o), Prince & Wooster St., New York, NY • “It’s her first day in the city, from South Africa. In South Africa there’s an animal called a ‘dassie’; it’s like a groundhog that lives in trees. She grew up with that and now she’s busy chasing squirrels in the city. We call them dassies, obviously. ‘Go get the dassies!’”

node.text: ADOPTABLE: Edward Milo, Lab mix (5 y/o), at @water4dogsnyc – Tribeca, NYC. Available via @camphappytailsnycrescue • “He was once a normal, able bodied, healthy dog. He loved running all day on his family’s ranch in Texas. Like a true southern boy, he’d always be home for supper. One day, he just didn’t return. They searched for him, and when they found him he was wailing and his back legs weren’t working. Sadly his original owners did him a disservice – the first 48 hours are crucial for dog spinal injuries like his. If he was able to get medical attention sooner, perhaps the damage could’ve been reversed. After that, he was put in a kill shelter. No one wanted to adopt him, being a large paralyzed dog with medical issues. We swooped in on the day he was set to be euthanized and took him in. It’s been a lot of work. The first couple of months he would spend six days a week here getting therapy. His legs need to be expressed nine times a day, he eats a special diet, he gets massages so his muscles don’t atrophy, red light treatment to stimulate cells, and he does water therapy, which he looks forward to so much. He’s got such a ‘pull yourself up by your bootstraps’ attitude. He’s such an inspiration and he’s one of our favorite campers of all time.”

We lived in Turkey for years and have been all over the U.S. His pet passport has a lot of stamps, but his favorite place is sleeping on top of our A/C.”
